One year ago at about this time we were handing Isaiah off to the doctors for his surgery knowing it’d be seven long hours before we held him again. Going through pictures and videos brought back all of the feels. What a little rockstar 🖤

Just touching on a common misconception I’m seeing pop up in my comments and messages lately. I completely understand that CIs aren’t for everyone but as far as the surgery destroying any residual hearing, that is no longer true. ( disclaimer: there are risks as with any surgery and residual hearing could be lost due to unexpected circumstances )

Drop any questions/topics about CIs you want me to touch on and I’ll try to answer them with a video this week and next! 🖤

✨your sign to start signing ✨I can’t even begin to tell you the amount of times I’ve been saved by the language, even though I’m not fluent. We’re learning everyday and it’s never too late to start. It doesn’t have to be hearing devices/spoken language OR signed language, it CAN be both. Just a couple situations where ASL has prevented language barrier frustration: 

1. Bedtime/Bath time when hearing devices are off. 
2. When the boys are sick or have a headache but do not want their devices.
3. Before they are able to get their point across with spoken language and need/want something but I’m not understanding…leading to tantrums & frustration (Isaiah is in this stage)
4. In a overstimulating environment 
5. At the dinner table and family functions when conversations are missed, they feel included with the language that comes most natural to them
6. When they are across the room and I need to tell them something but I don’t want to yell

#signlanguage #mom #deafkids #deaf #learningeveryday #languagebarrier
#littlesponges #raisingboys

I struggled with this but eventually realized that we can’t expect everyone to automatically understand when they haven’t lived it. Sharing your experiences, what you’ve learned, how you’ve grown, and what they can do to support you makes a huge difference. 

Sharing your truth doesn’t have to be public or in this space to help those around you understand, talking through challenges with those closest to you on a personal level is where the magic happens, it’s how you build your support system. Feeling like no one around you can relate is really, really lonely. But it doesn’t have to be. You have the ability to change the conversation. 🖤 

Also random fun fact: I still use pen and paper for all of my lists and journaling. I just can’t get down with it all being digital, I have to physically write it out. Are you a pen and paper person or a phone/computer person?! 📝

One of my most frequently asked questions is how we manage to keep our relationship healthy while navigating the added stress of this journey. I’m not a professional by any means but it took a while to realize that we needed to be on the same page 100% of the time. Instead of dealing with things on our own, we started leaning into the struggles together. With his busy work schedule and me often feeling lost in motherhood—nightly check-ins and making it a priority to get the kids to bed early once a week so we can have dinner with each other has made a huge difference. You’ve probably noticed that I’m not active in this space full time, and that’s important for us too. 

If you have any tips, drop them in the comments for someone who might be struggling with this. 🖤

Debated posting this because he is clearly frustrated, but I think it’s important for other CI parents to realize that even after four years, therapy, oral preschool, and sign language we still have communication struggles that often end in frustration. It’s a marathon not a sprint and it takes a ton of patience. (More patience than I ever thought I’d have) 

Video description: Silas came home from school wanting to watch a YouTube video that he watched at school. He was trying to explain the name of the video to mom, she did not understand and he was clearly frustrated from having to repeat himself. He didn’t know a sign for what he was trying to say. Eventually, they figured it out and he said “that’s more like it”. Text on screen reads: even after four years with cochlear implants and ASL, we still have communication struggles. Sometimes it takes us a while to figure it out and he gets really frustrated with me. I always continue to try to figure it out because clearly it’s important to him. I would have never in a million years guessed this, but we made it!)

“Are you just scared of having another deaf baby?” The possibility of another child with hearing loss has never and will never be a reason not to have another baby. Sure, it’s a lot of work. Takes a lot of time and patience. But hearing loss is not a reason to not have a baby. In fact, if it was feasible for us financially, we’ve talked about adopting a baby or two with hearing loss. 

My truth, I guess hard to understand, is that after multiple miscarriages and a still birth, my anxiety surrounding pregnancy and childbirth is almost unmanageable. It takes a toll on my mental health and doesn’t allow me to be the mom/wife I want to be. The constant worry and obsession that something will go wrong is something that’s really hard for me, and I’m not sure it’s a place I want to go back to. 

So in short — Do I want more babies? Yes. Could I handle another pregnancy? I’m not sure. Does the Connexin 26 hearing loss gene scare us? Absolutely not. 🦻🤟🏼

Happy 4th Heavenly Birthday to my angel baby, Eli. 👼🏼💙 We miss you every single day. 

Being a loss mom, you have to figure out how to live without being able to physically hold one of your children. You learn to live with the what ifs. You learn to live with wondering what their personality would be like. You learn to live with a feeling that something is missing from your life. And for me, (being very vulnerable here) sometimes that looks like blocking it out, not acknowledging the intense pain. Blocking out the way you can relive the day so vividly it’s as if it’s happening again. As bad as it may sound, sometimes it’s easier to pretend it didn’t happen and get lost in everything, anything else, because my anxiety is too high and I’m just trying to get through my day. Sometimes it looks like just going through the motions, not allowing anyone into my bubble for days at a time because I don’t have the emotional energy that it takes outside of caring for my children earth side. Sometimes it looks like crying on the bathroom floor because of a dream where there were three little boys at the park calling me mommy instead of two or because my oldest says he wants another brother to play with and he’s supposed to have one. Sometimes it’s holding my breath and saying a prayer when another one of my friends announces they are expecting because pregnancy and infant loss is forever ingrained into the back of my head. And sometimes, it’s holding my babies longer at night because I know it’s truly a miracle that they are here and they are healthy. 

I don’t think missing your child ever gets easier, you just get better at living with it. And living with it looks different for everyone. This is what it looks like for me.

When we talk about it out loud, it definitely seems like a lot. But thinking back to where we were when we met, its a miracle really. We both came out of rehab with a backpack full of clothes, a new mindset, and coping mechanisms that without inpatient treatment we would have never had. Before treatment, I didn’t cope with emotions, I numbed them. I think I can say the same for Steve. So in a way, that part of our life really prepared us for everything that was to come. 

Not long after finding out that Silas was deaf, communication was rocky because we were both grieving our child’s deafness in our own way. Both not really understanding what we needed ourselves let alone how to help each other. Eventually, we realized there were things that needed to be worked through together and things that needed to be worked through separately. We went back to the basics getting through one day at a time and weren’t too proud to get outside help, there was a lot of therapy involved for the both of us. The two of us still regularly speak to our own therapists, working through the emotional trauma of our past, losing a child, and raising deaf children as hearing parents. That last one isn’t something i consider to be traumatic any longer, but learning about your childs deafness as a hearing parent for the first time is definitely something that warrants emotional support. 

We’ve really put a lot of work into our communication, making sure we’re both in check with each others feelings, and always on the same page. We aren’t perfect by any means but I’m really proud of us for pushing through when things get hard. We make a really great team. 

One thing I’ve learned is that life happens. But how you react to it is what’s important.

Feeling frustrated because you feel like you put so much time and effort into language & development with your child but the progress isn’t there? I see you. 

Even if your play sessions are short and you feel like you’re not getting anything in return, chances are they’re absorbing information like little sponges. And eventually, all of that input will come flowing out when you least expect it. 

Focus on a language rich environment more than progress and it will come in time. Play time over perfection. Talking to your child over therapy. And more than anything, you both will benefit from the one on one time. 

It’s a marathon not a sprint. 🖤

Story time, a couple years ago we were playing in a the backyard with Silas (he was two at the time, probably Isaiah’s age) I literally blinked and he was gone. (There was a friend here with her children who will tell you the exact story @coachclarissa_ ) We had been playing in the sprinkler so he wasn’t wearing his processors. I looked in our front yard, backyard, in our house, yelled for him at the top of my lungs knowing he couldn’t hear me anyway. I flicked lights and stomped on the floor. Nothing. Within 5 minutes I called the police because I was not going to wait any longer……right before the police got here, he came walking out of the house. 😭 he was hiding and had zero clue I was looking for him. It was the scariest 10 minutes of my life…

I think this is the moment I realized how terrifying it would be to be separated from my child who is deaf in public, my biggest fear. Four years of marriage and some how it just keeps getting better. 🖤

Isaiah is talking up a storm at home, sometimes putting 2-3 words together, and beginning to ask questions like “what’s that?” The number of words he said at speech therapy today? ZERO. 

It’s really discouraging when you want the professionals you work with to see the progress your child has made since the last time you saw them but more often than not you’re stuck saying “I swear they do that at home” 

I’m just here to tell you that it’s normal. I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again, speech sessions at this age are more for you as a parent to learn and gain techniques to use at home with your child. The hour session twice a month isn’t getting them where they need to be, YOU ARE. So remember that next time you feel defeated, you know what they’re capable of and that’s what matters.

Someone asked me recently in a story question box if the boys would be able to go to college. I didn’t answer it because as innocent as it may have been, it kind of rubbed me the wrong way. The lack of understanding surrounding d/Deaf individuals…is mind blowing. But, If I’m being honest, I really shouldn’t let questions like this bother me, it’s an opportunity to educate. As embarrassing as it might be, five years ago I didn’t know what I didn’t know and I was able to learn…so others should have the opportunity as well. 

If the boys decide to go to college, they most certainly can. There is nothing they can’t do, except hear. There will come a time when there are challenges and obstacles, when people doubt their ability, when accessibility lacks and it makes things harder than they should be. My job is to is make sure they know how to work hard, fight for what they want/need and know if they put their mind to something, nothing will stop them. Not even their deafness. 

Fun fact: there are Deaf doctors & nurses, social workers, carpenters, electricians, paramedics + first responders, athletes, authors, actors, scientists, FBI agents, musicians, lawyers, engineers, mechanics… I could go on. 

So to answer the question I skipped: they are capable of anything they put their mind to.

Thank you so much @feliciaaquilo for featuring us with your audience! See what she said below about using our child safe temporary tattoos when taking her adorable sons, both deaf, into public. While her boys use cochlear implants they also communicate using ASL. Follow their journey to learn about total communication because we think they are pretty rad!

“Story time, a couple years ago we were playing in a the backyard with Silas (he was two at the time, probably Isaiah’s age) I literally blinked and he was gone. (There was a friend here with her children who will tell you the exact story @ coachclarissa_ ) We had been playing in the sprinkler so he wasn’t wearing his processors. I looked in our front yard, backyard, in our house, yelled for him at the top of my lungs knowing he couldn’t hear me anyway. I flicked lights and stomped on the floor. Nothing. Within 5 minutes I called the police because I was not going to wait any longer……right before the police got here, he came walking out of the house. 😭 he was hiding and had zero clue I was looking for him. It was the scariest 10 minutes of my life…

I think this is the moment I realized how terrifying it would be to be separated from my child who is deaf in public, my biggest fear. While Silas is a little older now and could probably read lips/tell someone his phone number even without his processors, I never want to be in a situation to find out. Ask anyone who knows my kids, they are fast and things happen.

These customizable temporary tattoos from my friend over at @bbxcraft have helped my anxiety surrounding public places with my children so much, I thought it was important to share. Not only for children who are deaf, but anyone with young kids planning family outings this summer.

Hello world! I’m going home!!!!! 💕 

Eden Elizabeth Aquilo, born December 27th at 12:40am. 6lbs 4oz of perfection. 

I’ve spent the last 17 weeks worrying about this sweet baby not knowing what to expect. So many tears. So many prayers. There were times Silas would talk about his baby sister and I would get upset and try to change the subject, trying to protect myself from the heartbreak. The doctors scared me. The internet scared me. The testing and scans scared me. Less than a month ago I had to meet with a neurosurgeon about brain surgery for my newborn and was told to expect a NICU stay. 

But here we are, just a little over 24 hours old, heading home. I cannot contain the happy tears. My little peanut. My sweet hummingbird. 🥹 

The worry is still there but it’s a different worry, she’s in my arms. She’s healthy. She’s perfection. I am over the moon.

I refuse to use the hospital wording and say she “failed” because what exactly is it that she failed? Her ability to hear doesn’t equal failing anything in life as you can see with my boys and it might be weird to some that I actually feel relief from this. We won’t know further details until her auditory brainstem response test later this month. 🫶🏻
